25|$|These {{ideas have}} largely framed or {{influenced}} all subsequent philosophical discussion and analysis. The specifics of Kant's account generated immediate and lasting controversy. Nevertheless, his thesesthat the mind itself necessarily makes a constitutive contribution to its knowledge, that this contribution is transcendental rather than psychological, <b>that</b> <b>philosophy</b> involves self-critical activity, that morality {{is rooted in}} human freedom, and that to act autonomously is to act according to rational moral principleshave all had a lasting effect on subsequent philosophy.|$|E
